                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">863.51 Relief Credits/222: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Edge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-02T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 2, 1930—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 2—1 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>126. Department’s 93, April 15, 6 p.m., to London. The French Government states
                    that the terms of the letter of April 16 last from Leith-Ross to the Austrian
                    Minister at London express the conditions to which it especially has
                    subordinated its adhesion to the emission of the Austrian loan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edge</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
